How to work with GIS¶

Geographic information system (GIS) is a system to capture and analyse spatial and geographical data.

It is often divided into two types of data:

  1. Vector data consisting of point, line (or arc), and polygon data. Polygon consists of geometries, which is formed of points. You may come across multipolygons, which are essentially multiple polygons grouped together.
  2. Raster data consisting of continuous or discrete features of surfaces and areas, such as topological information, population density, or satellite imagery.

For the Transport Systems module, you will be working with the vector data.

Vector GIS data is commonly stored in the shapefile format with related attribute data. These can be opened by commercial software packages such as ArcGIS by ESRI, creator of shapefiles, or QGIS.

Whilst the term shapefile sounds like there would be one singular file, a shapefile is a collection of multiple basic files:

  • *.shp   -   Main file (required) with the geometry data -- this often has the largest file size
  • *.shx   -   Index file (required) with the geometry data index
  • *.dbf   -   Attribute file (required) with the attribute information of features and geometry -- even with zero attributes, this is required.

  • *.prj   -   The file that stores the coordinate system information (optional).
  • *.cpg   -   The file that can be used to specify the codepage for identifying the character set to be used (optional).
  • *.sbn   -   One of the two files that store spatial index of the features (optional).
  • *.sbx   -   One of the two files that store spatial index of the features (optional).
  • *.xml   -   Metadata for information about the shapefile (optional).

All the files that form one shapefile needs to have the same prefix, e.g. roads.shp, roads.shx, roads.dbf, etc.

When using Python to process shapefiles, we will read in *.shp file, but all the other required files need to be present in the same folder.

One more important aspect to consider when working with GIS data is ensuring you are working in the same coordinate reference system (CRS) throughout your entire project. In this course, we will be using EPSG:4326 (WGS 84). This is the latitude and longitude CRS you will find when you Google London's latitude and longitude: 51.509865, -0.118092. However, shapefile geometry order is longitude then latitude.

Installation requirement¶

Now that we understand what the files are for, let's install and import the necessary packages for us to be able to work with shapefiles.

Within your conda environment tsenv, you will already have a few libraries installed from previous sessions:

  • numpy
  • pandas
  • matplotlib
  • scikit-learn (or sklearn)
  • pulp

We will now install geopandas, which is pandas for geospatial data. To do this, we need to first ensure to install GDAL (Geospatial Data Abstraction Library), which is a translator library for raster and vector geospatial data formats.

Regardless of having a Windows or Mac or Linux operating system, instead of pip install .., we will be using conda install ..:

conda install -c conda-forge gdal
conda install geopandas

If this didn't work, especially for those of you, who are using Windows, try using an alternative method following a YouTube video here.

Please contact your GTAs, if you are having trouble installing GDAL and/or Geopandas.

As part of the GeoPandas, a package called Shapely will be downloaded. This helps us work with GIS data of points, polygons, and multipolygons.

The example shapefile contains Lower Super Output Areas (LSOA) in Greater London. LSOAs are a geographic hierarchy designed to improve the reporting of small area statistics in England and Wales.

In this example, our shapefile contains the LSOA zone codes (or IDs), the name of the LSOAs, the number of households in each area and the average household size for each zone. Then most importantly, the data also contains the geometry details of the polygon, which forms the outline of each LSOA zone.

As mentioned, it is very important to note that the geometry in Geopandas is in order of longitude then latitude. If you get these mixed up, instead of analysing London, you may be analysing bits of the sea next to Somalia!

Geometric centroids¶

(You won't need to calculate your own centroids in your coursework, but this is how you would normally calculate the geometric centroids.)

Now, let's try to calculate geometric centroids of each LSOA.

One crucial note about the CRS of EPSG:4326 (WGS84). EPSG stands for European Petroleum Survey Group and now known as Geomatics Committee of the International Association of Oil and Gas Producers. They have various coordinate reference systems, and the one used on Google Maps is EPSG:4326, which is the same as WGS84. WGS stands for World Geodetic System. As the name already gives away, WGS84 or EPSG:4326 is based on a geodetic plane, which takes the curvature of the earth into account. (Contrary to what some believe, the earth is not flat!)

However, to calculate a geometric centroid, we want to know the plane area of each LSOA. To do this, for UK, we can use the ETRS89 Lambert Azimuthal Equal Area projection to "flatten" the surface of Europe. ETRS stands for European Terrestrial Reference System and this projection was created in 1989. This is equivalent to EPSG:3035. Depending on your geographical location, you may have to use a different EPSG to "flatten" your geometry, especially if you are studying an area outside of Europe, as the earth is not a perfect sphere.

In [5]:
# To convert the geometry
ldn_geo_3035 = ldn_df['geometry'].to_crs(epsg=3035)

You can see the polygon data is no longer in WGS84 format. Now the earth is flat, we can calculate the centroids.\

(You may come across a tempting funtion called GeoSeries.representative_point(). This is not the centroid, but just a very quick method of finding an arbitrary point in a polygon. This will give you the wrong result!)

Connecting centroids¶

Now that we have the centroids, imagine one of them connected to some of the other centroids. How can we visualise this on a plot?

First, we will choose a main centroid arbitrarily to connect to some randomly selected others. In your assignment, you need to connect your facility locations to the relevant centroids.

In [11]:
import random

n_random_centroids = 50

centroid_main = {'main': random.choice(ldn_df['centroids'])}
centroid_set_random = dict(zip(list('pt' + str(i+1) for i in range(n_random_centroids)), random.choices(ldn_df['centroids'], k=n_random_centroids)))

We will now connect centroid_random to other points in centroid_set_random.

    ax.scatter(x=v2.x, y=v2.y, s=50, color='crimson', marker='o') 

# Connect the random single centroid with the other chosen centroids
for k1,v1 in centroid_main.items():
    for k2,v2 in centroid_set_random.items():
        ax.plot([v1.x, v2.x],[v1.y,v2.y],
                color='green',alpha=0.5, linewidth=1)

# plt.axis('scaled')
legend = ax.legend()

How to calculate the distance between two points on earth.¶

We need to also learn to calculate the distance between two points on a map. You cannot take the Euclidean distance for such long distances and we need to take the earth's arc into account.

The following function will be useful to calculate the distance between two point using the haversine formula based on the radius of the earth at the latitude of London, 6365.078 km. The radius of the earth varies from 6356.752 km at the poles to 6378.137 km at the equator.

In [13]:
def haversine_np(lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2):
    """
    Calculate the great circle distance between two points
    on the earth (specified in decimal degrees)

    """
    
    r_earth = 6365.078
    lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2 = map(np.radians, [lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2])

    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1

    a = np.sin(dlat/2.0)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2.0)**2

    c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
    km = r_earth * c
    return km

Let's test the haversine_np function with our main centroid with the 2nd random centroid from our set.

In [14]:
dist = haversine_np(centroid_main['main'].x, centroid_main['main'].y, centroid_set_random['pt2'].x, centroid_set_random['pt2'].y)
print(f'Distance between the two points are {np.round(dist,2)} km.')

Distance between the two points are 15.91 km.

Creating a coverage matrix¶

We have 1 main centroid and 50 random centroids. However, out of the 50, let's say, I want to only select those within 15km. How will I find those that are covered within the 15km radius?

Using the Haversine distance calculator haversine_np from above, we will first create a distance dictionary from the main centroid to others in the set.

In [15]:
dist_dict = {}
for k1, v1 in centroid_main.items():
    for k2, v2 in centroid_set_random.items():
        dist_dict[(k1,k2)] = haversine_np(v1.x,v1.y,v2.x,v2.y)

We now want to create a new matrix where the value is 1, if a centroid from our set is within 15km of our main centroid. In Python, the matrix is in the form of a nested dictionary. This means that the dictionary has a key of the facility location and value with another dictionary of the delivery locations and the values of 1 to confirm coverage. For example,

coverage_matrix = {'facility1': {'A1':1, 'A3':1, 'A5':1}, 'facility2': {'A2':1, 'A5':1}, 'facility3': {'A1':1, 'A2':1, 'A3':1, 'A4':1}}

See Notebook 3.8.

In [16]:
max_distance = 15
coverage_matrix = {}
for k1, v1 in centroid_main.items():
    coverage_matrix[k1] = {}
    for k2, v2 in centroid_set_random.items():
        if dist_dict[(k1,k2)] <= max_distance:
            coverage_matrix[k1][k2] = 1
